England":"England","Ockbrook, Derbyshire, England":"Ockbrook, Derbyshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1135–1200":"1135–1200","1135–1171":"1135–1171","1136–Female":"1136–Deceased","1166–Female":"1166–Deceased","–1193":"–1193","–1228":"–1228","–Female":"Deceased","1110–1166":"1110–1166","1112–1166":"1112–1166","1228":"1228","about 1160":"about 1160","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1112":"1112","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","after 1166":"after 1166","26 June 1193":"26 June 1193","1193":"1193","1171":"1171","England":"England","Ockbrook, Derbyshire, England":"Ockbrook, Derbyshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzRalph was born in 1135, in Ockbrook, Derbyshire, England, his father, Ralph FitzGeremund, was 25 and his mother, Hawise Ockbrook, was 23. He married Edelina about 1160, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died in 1200, in England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1135–1200":"1135–1200","1135–1171":"1135–1171","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","1